{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528824"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14331"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.11,0.14,0.48,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89996"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"2212"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89996"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of right gluteal region pain. He denies any trauma or wound to the area and has no previous similar history. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes. His regular medications are metformin and gliclazide. He smokes 15 cigarettes per day and denies regular alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on 2 L/min oxygen, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. He is morbidly obese with a BMI of 42 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is a 5x5 cm area of erythema over the right gluteal region with some blistering. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 18 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 135 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 90 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 14 mmol/L (3.9-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["LRINEC score","CT pelvis","MRI pelvis","Emergency surgical debridement","Open cut down by the bedside"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs suggestive of necrotising fasciitis: fever, tachycardia, hypotension, and localised erythema with blister formation in the context of diabetes (a risk factor). Given the potential for rapid progression and high mortality associated with necrotising fasciitis, emergency surgical intervention is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency surgical debridement\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing necrotising fasciitis. It allows direct visualisation of the affected tissues, which is crucial for confirming the diagnosis and initiating appropriate treatment. During the procedure, surgeons can observe characteristic findings such as grey, necrotic fascia, lack of bleeding, and \u0027dishwater\u0027 fluid. This approach not only confirms the diagnosis but also serves as the primary treatment modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ELRINEC (Laboratory Risk Indicator for Necrotizing Fasciitis) score\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful tool for risk stratification in suspected cases of necrotising fasciitis. It incorporates laboratory values such as C-reactive protein, white blood cell count, haemoglobin, sodium, creatinine, and glucose levels. While a high score can raise suspicion, it is not definitive for diagnosis and should not delay surgical intervention if necrotising fasciitis is clinically suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in identifying gas in the soft tissues, which is suggestive of necrotising fasciitis. However, the absence of gas does not rule out the diagnosis. CT scans may also show fascial thickening and fluid collections. While useful, CT should not delay surgical intervention if there is high clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E can provide detailed soft tissue imaging and may show fascial thickening, fluid collections, and areas of necrosis. It is more sensitive than CT for detecting early stages of necrotising fasciitis. However, MRI is time-consuming and may not be readily available in emergency situations. Like CT, it should not delay surgical intervention if necrotising fasciitis is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen cut down by the bedside\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard procedure for diagnosing necrotising fasciitis. It lacks the controlled environment and comprehensive approach of a formal surgical debridement. Additionally, it may introduce infection if not performed under sterile conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, given the potential for rapid progression and high mortality associated with necrotising fasciitis, emergency surgical debridement is the most appropriate next step. It allows for both definitive diagnosis and immediate treatment, which is crucial in managing this life-threatening condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Emergency surgical debridement is the gold standard for diagnosing necrotising fasciitis, as it allows direct visualisation of the affected tissues.","The Laboratory Risk Indicator for Necrotising Fasciitis (LRINEC) score can aid in risk stratification but is not definitive for diagnosis of necrotising fasciitis.","Imaging studies such as CT and MRI can be helpful but may delay definitive treatment in suspected necrotising fasciitis."],"references":["Wong CH, Khin LW, Heng KS, Tan KC, Low CO. The LRINEC (Laboratory Risk Indicator for Necrotizing Fasciitis) score: a tool for distinguishing necrotizing fasciitis from other soft tissue infections. Crit Care Med. 2004 Jul;32(7):1535-41. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15241098/","Allaw F, Wehbe S, Kanj SS. Necrotizing fasciitis: an update on epidemiology, diagnostic methods, and treatment. Curr Opin Infect Dis. 2024 Apr 1;37(2):105-111. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38037890/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14331"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T16:17:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T16:17:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7026"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89996"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"